			<div class="postrow has_after_content">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Activist Indicted for Hacking into MIT and downloading scholarly articles
				</h2>
				

						
							
							
							
						
						
				<div class="content ">
					<div id="post_message_1693450">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							NY Times article: <a href="http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/07/19/reddit-co-founder-charged-with-data-theft/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/0...th-data-theft/</a><br />
<br />
msnbc <a href="http://technolog.msnbc.msn.com/_news/2011/07/19/7114056-reddit-connected-activist-indicted-in-mit-theft" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://technolog.msnbc.msn.com/_news...d-in-mit-theft</a><br />
<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				The publicly available indictment , filed by U.S. Attorney for the District of Massachusetts, Carmen M. Ortiz, describes Swartz's alleged indiscretions in full detail, listing multiple instances of his evasion of MIT's attempts to stop him from downloading documents en masse from JSTOR, a document and journal repository. Swartz is being charged with wire fraud, computer fraud, unlawfully obtaining information from a protected computer, and recklessly damaging a protected computer.
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>What a weird case.<br />
<br />
On the one hand, reading the indictment, Swartz was engaging in some really suspicious behavior.  Furthermore MIT did take steps to prevent the unknown user from accessing the files, and he continued circumenting those blocks.  The full indictment: <a href="https://www.documentcloud.org/documents/217115-20110719-schwartz.html" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">https://www.documentcloud.org/docume...-schwartz.html</a><br />
<br />
On the other hand, after the fact, MIT and JSTOR are not pressing charges and not suing for damages.  He was downloading academic papers, the kind stuff that it's almost a crime that it's NOT free for anyone to download.<br />
<br />
Plus there's this choice quote from asshole US Attorney Carmen Ortiz:<br />
<br />
<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				Stealing is stealing whether you use a computer command or a crowbar and whether you take documents, data or dollars. It is equally harmful to the victim whether you sell what you have stolen or give it away.
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>I hate her so much.<br />
<br />
Demand Progress site: <a href="http://blog.demandprogress.org" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://blog.demandprogress.org</a><br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
It's surreal.  The tinfoil-hat part of me that doesn't come out much thinks there must be some political motivation for this, but I'm not sure what it is.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
			<div class="after_content">
				
				<!-- edit note -->
