		<div class="postbody">
			<div class="postrow has_after_content">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: Activist Arrested for Hacking into MIT and downloading scholarly articles
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1693505">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>Alikat Astrae</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?p=1693469#post1693469" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">So MIT doesn't use any tax money to operate at all?  Because if MIT uses any public money to operate, then anything they create or produce ought to be in the public domain.</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>Man oh man do I wish it was able to work that way.  <br />
<br />
In the US at least (and every other country I deal with regularly), the NSF's budget is enough to fund ~10% of research proposals that come in every year.  ~10% total.  Research science can be a bit pricey, but even with research like mine which is inexpensive, finding funding is usually difficult because actually paying for research and scientific progress seems to be low on the totem pole.<br />
<br />
And there is the problem.  To get a journal actually published requires a rather large amount of money, and that money is made up by 2 means usually.<br />
<br />
(1) Subscription fee's, which are usually quite small for an individual (and especially small for an individual student), and are pretty small from an institutional standpoint as well.<br />
<br />
(2) Publication costs:  This varies widely from journal to journal, and as a function of how long/short an article is, how many figures, how many color figures, etc.<br />
<br />
Most of the better run/organized journals have limited publication costs, unless you start getting into color figures, at which point is can be $1000/figure +/- $500 depending.  Most of these journals budgets are covered by subscriptions.   This means that these journals have a vested interest in keeping at least a modicum of control over the articles.  Because they are businesses, and must balance costs/revenue to stay IN business.  But bear in mind, every journal I know is a non-profit, they're just trying to 'make' money, they are just trying to not lose money!<br />
<br />
While I would LOVE NSF/NIH to actually run/publish their own journals, and have them be completely open access, but to do so would completely eat the NSF's budget for a year, and it seems that nobody wants to raise the budget for publicly funded research in this country anyways.<br />
<br />
The articles themselves are, for all intents and purposes, open access, they just require you going to a public library and looking it up, and at worst, waiting a few days/weeks for an InterLibrary Loan to come in.  No matter how obscure the journal, or article, I've never had to wait more then a month to get a copy of an article free of charge, the request just has to percolate through the proper channels.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
			<div class="after_content">
				
                                       
                                 
				
		        		<blockquote class="signature restore"><div class="signaturecontainer">&quot;We live in a society absolutely dependent on science and technology and yet have cleverly arranged things so that almost no one understands science and technology. That's a clear prescription for disaster.&quot; <br />
-Carl Sagan</div></blockquote>
				
                                        
			</div>
			
			<div class="cleardiv"></div>
		</div>
	</div>
