				<div class="message">Cost of a JSTOR membership is $40 a year or so. Glad my tax dollars are being spent hunting down a person trying to learn shit off the internet.</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>Only for a small subset of the JSTOR library.  MIT's JSTOR library was comprehensive and could have [b]<a href="http://www.boston.com/news/local/massachusetts/articles/2011/07/20/activist_charged_with_hacking_mit_network_to_download_files/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">cost over $50,000 a year.</a>  This punk was also not just stealing over 4 million documents; he was also breaking-and-entering, hard-wired himself to the network in a supply closet on campus, and covering his face while he stole documents he intended to distribute for free on peer-to-peer networks.  <br />
<br />
Look, I want information to be free as much as the next person.  But this kid has a history of asshattery.  For example, he claims he &quot;co-founded&quot; Reddit (and if you ask the media, they will list him as a co-founder).  However, Reddit was already established when he hopped on the bandwagon and helped promote it; he invented nothing, but peddles himself as some sort of web genius.<br />
<br />
I hope he gets the maximum penalty of 35 years in prison.  Karma's a bitch.
