			<span class="usertitle">
				
				It's not so bad<br>
				
				
			</span>
			
			
			
			 
			
				<hr />
				<dl class="userinfo_extra">
					<dt>Join Date</dt> <dd>Jun 2003</dd>
					
					
					<dt>Posts</dt> <dd>11,171</dd>	
					
				</dl>
				
				
				<div class="imlinks">
					    
				</div>
			
		</div>
		<div class="postbody">
			<div class="postrow has_after_content">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: Activist Arrested for Hacking into MIT and downloading scholarly articles
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1693515">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>Zumino Zufeilon</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?p=1693505#post1693505" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">Publication costs:  This varies widely from journal to journal, and as a function of how long/short an article is, how many figures, how many color figures, etc.<br />
<br />
Most of the better run/organized journals have limited publication costs, unless you start getting into color figures, at which point is can be $1000/figure +/- $500 depending.  Most of these journals budgets are covered by subscriptions.   This means that these journals have a vested interest in keeping at least a modicum of control over the articles.  Because they are businesses, and must balance costs/revenue to stay IN business.  But bear in mind, every journal I know is a non-profit, they're just trying to 'make' money, they are just trying to not lose money!<br />
<br />
While I would LOVE NSF/NIH to actually run/publish their own journals, and have them be completely open access, but to do so would completely eat the NSF's budget for a year, and it seems that nobody wants to raise the budget for publicly funded research in this country anyways.<br />
<br />
The articles themselves are, for all intents and purposes, open access, they just require you going to a public library and looking it up, and at worst, waiting a few days/weeks for an InterLibrary Loan to come in.  No matter how obscure the journal, or article, I've never had to wait more then a month to get a copy of an article free of charge, the request just has to percolate through the proper channels.</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>Why is it necessary to have any of this on paper any more? There should be no extra expense for 'being in colour' in 2011!<br />
<br />
The people submitting the article should be paying any expense required to decently format it, so that shouldn't be a cost for the journal. And it's not like it's not going to have been done electronically internally to begin with. What, so the scientists are going to have been communicating the original research and submitting it for internal review <i>on paper</i>? Of course not.<br />
<br />
The only cost the journal should need to suffer is if it has experts on retainer for peer review or fact-checking purposes. Apart from that the whole thing could be virtually done on a 'wiki' basis and cost almost nothing.<br />
<br />
Why isn't this the way things have gone already? Why is there any requirement for paper-based any more especially now that eReaders and tablets are becoming increasingly ubiquitous? Why isn't it far more convenient for the articles to be online only - available to be printed off only if someone absolutely must have it on paper?
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
			<div class="after_content">
				
                                       
                                 
				
		        		<blockquote class="signature restore"><div class="signaturecontainer">I hear and I forget. I see and I remember. I do and I understand</div></blockquote>
				
                                        
			</div>
			
			<div class="cleardiv"></div>
		</div>
	</div>
